   <abstract>Early map of Nashville detailing the street grid, various public buildings, engravings of prominent buildings, and the Cumberland River. Wards are faintly colored. The courthouse, jail, city hall, market houses, banks, theaters, post offices, hotels, churches, schools, factories, and mills are all indicated and labeled in the references list in the bottom right corner. Surrounding the map are engravings of prominent buildings including Christ Church, University of Nashville, View of Nashville from Rock Castle, Tennessee Penitentiary, Baptist Church, Yeatman Woods &amp; Co. Bank, Methodist Episcopal Church, Nashville from the margin of the river below the city, Nashville Female Academy, the Courthouse, Nashville from Brown's Eminence, the Hermitage, Rock Castle, Meridian Hill, Park Cottage, Elm Wood, Mr. Bateman's Inn, Part of the Public Square Market House, Presbyterian Church, and the U. S. Branch Bank.</abstract>
   <abstract>This map represents the earliest detailed plan of Nashville. The street grid, public buildings, engravings of various buildings, and the Cumberland River all combine to create what contemporaries deemed a "beautiful specimen of art." John P. Ayres opened up a bookstore in Nashville's Public Square on August 14, 1834.</abstract>
